i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 29 Jun 2010 13:10:50 -0700";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1873:"<p>I updated my <a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com/emergency-wordpress-access/">Emergency WordPress access</a> script today, because of some issues we''d discovered at OrangeValley and some bugs submitted by users. When I updated the post, I realized I should be emailing all the commenters, as some of them had had the same issue, and most of them would want the updated script.</p><p>Quite a while back I''d written a plugin for exactly that purpose, called <a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com/wordpress/email-commenters/">email commenters</a>. It had some small issues though, and I hadn''t updated it for quite a while, but thought tonight was a good time to do just that. So I updated it, and it now gives you a link in the top right of the post to email all users:</p><p><img\n src="http://cdn.yoast.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/email-commenters.png" alt="" title="email-commenters" width="390" height="172" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2731"/></p><p>An easy way to let people know that you''ve updated a post. Search for "email commenters" in your backend, install the plugin and activate: no need to do more. Let me know what you think in the comments, should I add something?</p><p><a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com/email-commenters-v1/">Emailing your commenters</a> is a post from <a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>''s <a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/joostdevalk/~4/JglNmzP_pnI" height="1" width="1"/>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:2:{s:7:"content";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:36:"\n            \n            \n         ";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:2:{s:6:"medium";s:5:"image";s:3:"url";s:68:"http://cdn.yoast.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/email-commenters.png";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:2:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"email-commenters";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:4:"type";s:4:"html";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:3:"url";s:76:"http://cdn.yoast.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/email-commenters-125x125.png";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}}s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:3:"url";s:76:"http://cdn.yoast.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/email-commenters-125x125.png";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:42:"http://rssnamespace.org/feedburner/ext/1.0";a:1:{s:8:"origLink";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:100:"http://yoast.com/email-commenters-v1/#utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=email-commenters-v1";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:12;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:97:"\n         \n         \n         \n         \n         \n         \n         \n         \n         \n      ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:4:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:56:"Yoast: Debugging your XML sitemap with an XSL Stylesheet";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:58:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/joostdevalk/~3/MuwAzKebKXM/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:922:"<p>When you&#39;re developing XML sitemaps, no matter on what platform, it&#39;s pretty hard to debug them sometimes to be proper XML. You have to validate all the time and you can&#39;t do a quick "glance" over to see whether your sitemap has the URL&#39;s you were expecting. As mentioned before I&#39;m working on my WordPress [...]</p><p><a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com/xsl-stylesheet-xml-sitemap/">Debugging your XML sitemap with an XSL Stylesheet</a> is a post from <a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don&#39;t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:24:"http://yoast.com/?p=2719";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 28 Jun 2010 13:16:30 -0700";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3624:"<p>When you''re developing XML sitemaps, no matter on what platform, it''s pretty hard to debug them sometimes to be proper XML. You have to validate all the time and you can''t do a quick "glance" over to see whether your sitemap has the URL''s you were expecting.</p><p>As mentioned before I''m working on my WordPress SEO plugin, and it''ll do sitemaps, three kinds of sitemaps actually: video, news and normal. For all three of them I''ve developed so called XSL stylesheets, so I can quickly glance over a sitemap and get an idea as to whether everything I expected to be in there is actually there. An XSL stylesheets transforms an XML document into HTML output, for instance, for a normal XML sitemap, that looks like this:</p><div\n id="attachment_2720" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width:310px;"><a rel="nofollow"\n class="thickbox" target="_blank" href="http://cdn.yoast.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/Styled-XML-Sitemap.png"><img\n src="http://cdn.yoast.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/Styled-XML-Sitemap-300x154.png" alt="Styled XML Sitemap" title="Styled XML Sitemap" width="300" height="154" class="size-medium wp-image-2720"/></a><p\n class="wp-caption-text">Click for larger image</p></div><p>And for an XML video sitemap:</p><div\n id="attachment_2722" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width:310px;"><a rel="nofollow"\n class="thickbox" target="_blank" href="http://cdn.yoast.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/Styled-XML-Video-Sitemap.png"><img\n src="http://cdn.yoast.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/Styled-XML-Video-Sitemap-300x166.png" alt="Styled XML Video Sitemap" title="Styled XML Video Sitemap" width="300" height="166" class="size-medium wp-image-2722"/></a><p\n class="wp-caption-text">Click for larger image</p></div><p>Especially with the recent addons to the sitemaps protocol (check out the image count in the first "normal" sitemap for instance), this makes it a lot easier to see if you''re doing things wrong. On top of that, using some jQuery, the headers are sortable!</p><h2>Download</h2><p>Because I know you want your own XML sitemaps to look this good too, I''ll release my XSL stylesheets here:</p><p><a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href=''http://cdn.yoast.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/xsl-stylesheets.zip''>XSL stylesheets for XML Sitemaps</a></p><h2>Usage</h2><p>Usage of these XSL stylesheets is easy, just add a line like this to the top of your XML output:</p><div\n class="wp_syntax"><div\n class="code"><pre class="xml" style="font-family:monospace;"><span style="color:#009900;"><span style="color:#000000;font-weight:bold;"><?xml-stylesheet</span> <span style="color:#000066;">type</span>=<span style="color:#ff0000;">"text/xsl"</span> <span style="color:#000066;">href</span>=<span style="color:#ff0000;">"/url/to/xsl-stylesheet.xsl"</span><span style="color:#000000;font-weight:bold;">?></span></span></pre></div></div><p>Let me know whether you like this, and what you''d like to add to these XSL stylesheets!</p><p><a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com/xsl-stylesheet-xml-sitemap/">Debugging your XML sitemap with an XSL Stylesheet</a> is a post from <a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>''s <a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a rel="nofollow"\n target="_blank" href="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/joostdevalk/~4/MuwAzKebKXM" height="1" width="1"/>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:2:{s:7:"content";a:2:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:49:"\n            \n            \n            \n         ";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:2:{s:6:"medium";s:5:"image";s:3:"url";s:70:"http://cdn.yoast.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/Styled-XML-Sitemap.png";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:29:"http://search.yaho